"""
era_parables.py — The Parables of Enoch (1 Enoch 37-71)

The Book of Parables (also called the Similitudes of Enoch) is the second
major division of 1 Enoch, comprising chapters 37-71. It is the ONLY section
of 1 Enoch not attested among the Dead Sea Scrolls — no Aramaic fragments
have been found at Qumran. At Qumran, the position occupied by the Parables
in the Ethiopic canon was filled by the Book of Giants (4Q530-532).

The Parables are structured as three "parables" or "similitudes" (meshalim):
  37      — Superscription and introduction
  38-44   — First Parable: the coming judgment, the Elect One, heavenly secrets
  45-57   — Second Parable: the Son of Man, the Head of Days, the fate of kings
  58-69   — Third Parable: blessedness of the saints, Noahic appendix, final judgment
  70-71   — Epilogue: Enoch's assumption and identification as the Son of Man

The central theological contribution is the figure of the "Son of Man" /
"Elect One" / "Righteous One" — a pre-existent, enthroned messianic judge
who sits on the throne of glory and executes judgment over kings and the
mighty. This figure draws heavily on Daniel 7:13-14 but develops the
Danielic vision in revolutionary directions: the Son of Man is named before
creation, hidden in God's presence, and ultimately revealed as Enoch himself.

Date: Scholarly consensus places the Parables in the late 1st century BC to
early 1st century AD (ca. 40 BC - 70 AD). The absence from Qumran sets
a terminus post quem of roughly the mid-1st century BC. The absence of any
clear reference to the destruction of the Temple (70 AD) suggests a date
before that event. J.T. Milik's proposal of a late Christian date (270 AD)
has been almost universally rejected. Key arguments for a pre-Christian or
early 1st century date include: (1) no distinctively Christian theology,
(2) the Parthian invasion references in ch. 56 fit 40 BC, (3) the "Son of
Man" usage differs from the Gospels in significant ways.

The Parables survive only in Ethiopic (Ge'ez). No Greek version is extant.
The underlying Semitic original was likely composed in Hebrew or Aramaic.

Translation references: R.H. Charles (1912), E. Isaac (OTP, 1983),
G.W.E. Nickelsburg & J.C. VanderKam (2012), M.A. Knibb (1978),
D.W. Suter (1979), J.J. Collins (1998).
"""

