        "divine_council_note": "The phrase 'Mine Elect One shall sit on the throne of "
                               "glory' is spoken by the Lord of Spirits himself — God "
                               "declaring the enthronement of his chosen agent. The "
                               "possessive 'Mine' emphasizes the relationship: the Elect "
                               "One is the Lord of Spirits' own representative. This is "
                               "delegated authority within the council, not autonomous "
                               "power. The 'throne of glory' (Ge'ez: manbar sebhat) is "
                               "the same throne that God sits on — the Elect One shares "
                               "God's seat. This shared-throne theology is the most "
                               "direct precursor to the NT's 'seated at the right hand "
                               "of God' (Mark 16:19, Heb 1:3).",

        "sections": [
            {
                "heading": "The Denial of the Lord of Spirits (45:1-2)",
                "body": "The second Parable opens with the fate of 'those who deny "
                        "the name of the Lord of Spirits.' The specific sin named "
                        "here is not moral failure in general but denial — the "
                        "refusal to acknowledge God's sovereignty. This is the "
                        "Parables' defining sin, repeated throughout the judgment "
                        "scenes. The kings and mighty deny the Lord of Spirits not "
                        "through ignorance but through arrogance: they trust in "
                        "their own power rather than God's authority. This criterion "
                        "maps directly onto Jesus' warning: 'Whoever denies me "
                        "before others, I also will deny before my Father in heaven' "
