        ],

        "cross_refs": [
            {"ref": "Daniel 7:9-14", "note": "The Ancient of Days with hair 'white like wool' and the one 'like a son of man' coming on clouds — the direct source for 1 Enoch 46", "type": "ot"},
            {"ref": "Matthew 26:63-64", "note": "Jesus tells the high priest he will see 'the Son of Man seated at the right hand of Power and coming on the clouds' — combining Daniel 7 with the enthroned figure of the Parables", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Revelation 1:13-16", "note": "One like a son of man with hair white as wool — Revelation combines the Ancient of Days and Son of Man descriptions", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Psalm 110:1", "note": "The LORD says to my lord: Sit at my right hand — the two-throne theology underlying both the Parables and NT christology", "type": "ot"},
            {"ref": "Philippians 2:9-11", "note": "God gave him the name above every name — the Son of Man's pre-eminence before the Lord of Spirits in 1 Enoch 46:3 anticipates this", "type": "nt"}
        ],

        "divine_council_note": "The Son of Man in chapter 46 occupies a unique position "
                               "in the divine council: he is neither the Most High (the "
                               "Lord of Spirits / Head of Days) nor a mere angel. He is "
                               "a second enthroned figure who shares the divine prerogatives "
                               "of judgment and sovereignty. This 'two powers in heaven' "
                               "theology was deeply controversial in Judaism. The rabbis "
                               "eventually rejected it as heresy (b. Sanhedrin 38b, "
                               "b. Hagigah 15a), but the concept was foundational for "
                               "early Christian christology.",

        "sections": [
            {
                "heading": "The Vision of the Head of Days (46:1)",
                "body": "Enoch sees 'One who had a head of days, and His head was "
                        "white like wool' — unmistakable language from Daniel 7:9 "
                        "('the Ancient of Days took his seat; his clothing was white "
                        "as snow, and the hair of his head like pure wool'). The "
                        "Parables use 'Head of Days' (Ge'ez: re'sa mawael) rather "
                        "than 'Ancient of Days' — a slight variation that emphasizes "
                        "primacy rather than mere antiquity. The white-wool imagery "
                        "signifies wisdom, purity, and eternal age. Notably, "
                        "Revelation 1:14 applies the 'white as wool' description "
                        "to the risen Christ, conflating the Ancient of Days and "
                        "Son of Man descriptions into a single figure."
            },
            {
                "heading": "The Son of Man Identified (46:2-4)",
                "body": "Walking with the Head of Days is 'another being whose "
                        "countenance had the appearance of a man, and his face was "
                        "full of graciousness, like one of the holy angels' (46:1). "
                        "The Son of Man's face is 'like one of the holy angels' — "
                        "he has an angelic appearance yet is specifically 'like a "
                        "man.' This ambiguity (human-like yet angel-like) mirrors "
                        "Daniel 7:13 where the figure is 'like a son of man' — "
                        "the comparison preserves mystery about the figure's exact "
                        "nature. Enoch asks three questions: who is he, where does "
                        "he come from, and why does he accompany the Head of Days? "
                        "The angel answers: 'This is the Son of Man who hath "
                        "righteousness, with whom dwelleth righteousness, and who "
                        "revealeth all the treasures of that which is hidden, "
                        "because the Lord of Spirits hath chosen him' (46:3). Four "
                        "traits define the Son of Man: inherent righteousness, "
                        "hidden knowledge, divine election, and eternal pre-eminence."
            },
            {
                "heading": "The Overthrow of Kings (46:4-8)",
                "body": "The Son of Man will 'put down the kings and the mighty from "
                        "their seats, and the strong from their thrones' (46:4). He "
                        "will 'loosen the reins of the strong, and crush the teeth "
                        "of the sinners' (46:4). The language is violent and total — "
                        "this is not reform but overthrow. The kings' specific sin is "
                        "identified: they 'deny the Lord of Spirits and His Anointed' "
                        "(46:8, some manuscripts). This pairing — Lord of Spirits and "
                        "His Anointed — echoes Psalm 2:2: 'The kings of the earth "
                        "set themselves... against the LORD and against his anointed.' "
                        "The Parables apply the Psalm 2 rebellion scenario to their "
                        "eschatological framework: the kings who oppose God and his "
                        "agent will be destroyed."
            }
        ]
    },

    {
        "id": "1en-47",
        "ref": "1 Enoch 47",
        "chapter_num": 47,
        "title": "The Prayer of the Righteous and the Blood of the Saints",
        "era": "parables",
        "type": "chapter",

        "synopsis": "The righteous cry out and their prayers ascend from the earth, "
                    "petitioning the Lord of Spirits for justice. The 'blood of the "
                    "righteous' is required from the earth. The holy ones in heaven "
                    "unite in supplication on behalf of the blood that has been shed. "
                    "The Head of Days sits on the throne, and the books of the living "
                    "are opened before him.",

        "key_verse": {
            "ref": "1 Enoch 47:1-2",
            "text": "And in those days shall have ascended the prayer of the "
                    "righteous, and the blood of the righteous from the earth "
                    "before the Lord of Spirits.",
            "translation": "Charles"
        },

        "hebrew_terms": [],
        "ane_backdrop": "The motif of shed blood crying out from the earth originates "
                        "in Genesis 4:10. The concept that innocent blood pollutes the "
                        "land and demands vindication is deeply embedded in ANE "
                        "jurisprudence and Israelite law (Numbers 35:33).",

        "second_temple": [],

        "cross_refs": [
            {"ref": "Revelation 6:9-11", "note": "Souls under the altar cry 'How long, O Lord, until you judge and avenge our blood?' — the closest NT parallel to 1 Enoch 47", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Genesis 4:10", "note": "'Your brother's blood cries out to me from the ground' — the prototype for blood demanding justice", "type": "ot"},
            {"ref": "Daniel 7:10", "note": "The court sat in judgment and the books were opened — 1 Enoch 47:3's opened books parallel the Danielic scene", "type": "ot"},
            {"ref": "Revelation 20:12", "note": "Books were opened, and the dead were judged by what was written — combining 1 Enoch 47 and Daniel 7", "type": "nt"}
        ],

        "divine_council_note": "The prayers of the righteous ascend to the divine court "
                               "as a formal petition. The 'holy ones in heaven' join the "
                               "petition, creating a united appeal from both earth and "
                               "heaven. The opening of books is a judicial act: the "
                               "council convenes and the evidence is presented.",

        "sections": [
            {
                "heading": "The Cry of the Righteous (47:1-2)",
                "body": "Prayer and martyrdom are linked as a single appeal to heaven. "
                        "The blood functions as a witness (cf. Hebrews 12:24). The "
                        "angels join the petition, creating liturgical solidarity "
                        "between earthly martyrs and the heavenly court. This pattern "
                        "appears in Revelation 5:8 where elders hold 'bowls of "
                        "incense, which are the prayers of the saints.'"
            },
            {
                "heading": "The Books Opened (47:3-4)",
                "body": "The Head of Days sits on the throne and the books are opened "
                        "— the judicial metaphor from Daniel 7:10. The 'books of the "
                        "living' record the deeds of all humanity and serve as "
                        "evidence in the cosmic trial. This motif develops through "
                        "Revelation 20:12 into the Christian Book of Life tradition."
            }
        ]
    },

    {
        "id": "1en-48",
        "ref": "1 Enoch 48",
        "chapter_num": 48,
        "title": "The Pre-Existence of the Son of Man — Named Before Creation",
        "era": "parables",
        "type": "chapter",

        "synopsis": "The Son of Man was 'named in the presence of the Lord of Spirits "
                    "before the sun and stars were created.' He is 'the light of the "
                    "Gentiles' and 'the hope of those who are troubled of heart.' "
                    "The kings who deny the Lord of Spirits and His Anointed will "
                    "face inescapable anguish. This chapter contains the Parables' "
                    "most radical christological claim: the pre-cosmic existence of "
                    "the messianic Son of Man.",

        "key_verse": {
            "ref": "1 Enoch 48:2-3",
            "text": "And at that hour that Son of Man was named in the presence "
                    "of the Lord of Spirits, and his name before the Head of Days. "
                    "Yea, before the sun and the signs were created, before the "
                    "stars of the heaven were made, his name was named before the "
                    "Lord of Spirits.",
            "translation": "Charles"
        },

        "hebrew_terms": [],

        "ane_backdrop": "In the Enuma Elish, naming IS creating: 'When on high the "
                        "heaven had not been named, firm ground below had not been "
                        "called by name.' The Parables use this convention to assert "
                        "the Son of Man's identity was established before the cosmos. "
                        "Rabbinic tradition (b. Pesachim 54a) lists the 'Name of the "
                        "Messiah' among seven things conceived before the world.",

        "second_temple": [
            {
                "source": "b. Pesachim 54a / b. Nedarim 39b",
                "summary": "Seven things created before the world: Torah, Repentance, "
                           "Garden of Eden, Gehenna, Throne of Glory, Temple, and the "
                           "Name of the Messiah.",
                "relevance": "The 'Name of the Messiah' as pre-existent parallels "
                             "1 Enoch 48:3 directly, showing this was a broader Jewish "
                             "tradition, not unique to the Parables.",
                "canon": False
            }
        ],

        "cross_refs": [
            {"ref": "John 1:1-3", "note": "'In the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God' — Johannine pre-existence parallels 1 Enoch 48", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "John 17:5", "note": "'Glorify me with the glory I had with you before the world existed' — Jesus claims the pre-cosmic existence attributed to the Son of Man", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Colossians 1:15-17", "note": "'He is before all things' — Pauline pre-existence christology mapping onto the Parables", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Isaiah 42:6; 49:6", "note": "'A light for the nations' — 1 Enoch 48:4 applies this Servant language to the Son of Man", "type": "ot"},
            {"ref": "1 Peter 1:20", "note": "Christ 'foreknown before the foundation of the world' — pre-existence through divine foreknowledge", "type": "nt"}
        ],

        "divine_council_note": "The 'naming' of the Son of Man before creation is a "
                               "council act: the Lord of Spirits designates his agent "
                               "before the cosmos exists. This is the most radical form "
                               "of pre-existence in Second Temple Judaism.",

        "sections": [
            {
                "heading": "The Fountain of Righteousness (48:1)",
                "body": "Enoch sees an 'inexhaustible fountain of righteousness' "
                        "surrounded by 'many fountains of wisdom' (48:1). The imagery "
                        "draws on Proverbs 13:14 and Jeremiah 2:13. Righteousness "
                        "is the inexhaustible source; wisdom flows from it."
            },
            {
                "heading": "Named Before Creation (48:2-3)",
                "body": "The claim that the Son of Man was 'named before the Lord of "
                        "Spirits before the creation of the sun and stars' asserts "
                        "pre-cosmic existence. Scholars debate whether this is 'ideal' "
                        "pre-existence (a plan in God's mind) or 'real' pre-existence "
                        "(actual being). The language supports the latter: the Son of "
                        "Man is 'named in the presence of' God — he is there, present. "
                        "This surpasses Daniel 7, where the Son of Man appears at "
                        "judgment but is not said to pre-exist."
            },
            {
                "heading": "Light of the Gentiles (48:4-7)",
                "body": "The Son of Man is 'the light of the Gentiles, and the hope "
                        "of those who are troubled of heart' (48:4). This language "
                        "comes directly from Isaiah 42:6 and 49:6. The Parables merge "
                        "three OT traditions: (1) the Danielic Son of Man, (2) the "
                        "Isaianic Servant, and (3) the Davidic Messiah. This threefold "
                        "merger is precisely what Christianity claimed about Jesus."
            },
            {
                "heading": "The Denial of the Lord of Spirits and His Anointed (48:8-10)",
                "body": "The kings 'have denied the Lord of Spirits and His Anointed' "
                        "(48:10). The pairing echoes Psalm 2:2 and provides one of the "
                        "Parables' uses of the mashiach title. Their reliance on 'the "
                        "works of their hands' will prove futile on the day of anguish."
            }
        ]
    },

