                    "the kings, so that a spirit of unrest shall come upon them.",
            "translation": "Charles"
        },

        "hebrew_terms": [],

        "ane_backdrop": "The 'armies from the east' draws on Israelite experience "
                        "with Mesopotamian invasion. The Parthian invasion of 40 BC "
                        "under Pacorus I — capturing Jerusalem and installing "
                        "Antigonus as puppet king — is the most likely reference.",

        "second_temple": [],

        "cross_refs": [
            {"ref": "Isaiah 13:17-19", "note": "'I am stirring up the Medes against them' — God using eastern armies as instruments of judgment", "type": "ot"},
            {"ref": "Revelation 9:13-16", "note": "Angels at the Euphrates released — the Apocalypse's eastern invasion motif", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Revelation 16:12", "note": "'The kings from the east' — Revelation drawing on the Enochic tradition", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Ezekiel 38-39", "note": "Gog and Magog invasion — OT apocalyptic invasion background", "type": "ot"}
        ],

        "divine_council_note": "The angels 'stir up' the kings — the invasion is "
                               "divinely orchestrated. The council uses human armies "
                               "as instruments of judgment (cf. Isaiah 10:5-6).",

        "sections": [
            {
                "heading": "The Parthian Reference (56:5-7)",
                "body": "The mention of 'Parthians and Medes' is the most important "
                        "datum for dating the Parables. The Parthian invasion of "
                        "40 BC best explains this imagery. The invaders being "
                        "'swallowed up' may reflect Herod's Roman-backed reconquest "
                        "of 37 BC. Scholars dating the Parables to ca. 40-30 BC "
                        "rely heavily on this passage."
            }
        ]
    },

