    {
        "id": "1en-60",
        "ref": "1 Enoch 60",
        "chapter_num": 60,
        "title": "The Noahic Fragment — Leviathan and Behemoth",
        "era": "parables",
        "type": "chapter",

        "synopsis": "A major Noahic interpolation. Enoch (speaking as Noah in this "
                    "passage) sees the Head of Days seated on his throne and trembles. "
                    "Michael explains the secrets of creation. The chapter describes "
                    "Leviathan (the female monster of the sea) and Behemoth (the "
                    "male monster of the dry land) separated on the fifth day of "
                    "creation — one to the sea, one to the desert of Dundain. "
                    "Cosmological secrets about thunder, winds, and the deep "
                    "are revealed.",

        "key_verse": {
            "ref": "1 Enoch 60:7-8",
            "text": "And on that day were two monsters parted, a female monster "
                    "named Leviathan, to dwell in the abysses of the ocean over "
                    "the fountains of the waters. But the male is named Behemoth, "
                    "who occupied with his breast a waste wilderness named "
                    "Duidain.",
            "translation": "Charles"
        },

        "hebrew_terms": [],

        "ane_backdrop": "Leviathan and Behemoth draw on deep ANE mythology. The "
                        "Ugaritic Lotan (= Leviathan) is the seven-headed sea "
                        "serpent defeated by Baal. Behemoth appears as a primordial "
                        "land creature in Job 40:15-24. The separation of the two "
                        "cosmic monsters — one to sea, one to land — reflects the "
                        "ANE cosmogonic tradition of taming chaos at creation.",

        "second_temple": [
            {
                "source": "4 Ezra 6:49-52",
                "summary": "On the fifth day, God separated Behemoth and Leviathan "
                           "because the waters could not hold both together.",
                "relevance": "An independent attestation of the same tradition, "
                             "confirming it was widespread in Second Temple Judaism.",
                "canon": False
            }
        ],

        "cross_refs": [
            {"ref": "Job 40:15-24", "note": "The description of Behemoth — the canonical source for the Parables' land monster", "type": "ot"},
            {"ref": "Job 41:1-34", "note": "The description of Leviathan — the canonical source for the sea monster", "type": "ot"},
            {"ref": "Isaiah 27:1", "note": "'In that day the LORD will punish Leviathan' — the eschatological destruction of the chaos monster", "type": "ot"},
            {"ref": "Revelation 13:1, 11", "note": "A beast from the sea and a beast from the earth — the Apocalypse's two monsters reflecting the Leviathan/Behemoth pair", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Psalm 74:13-14", "note": "'You broke the heads of Leviathan' — the creation-battle tradition", "type": "ot"}
        ],

        "divine_council_note": "The separation of Leviathan and Behemoth is a council "
                               "act — God assigns each monster to its domain, imposing "
                               "order on primordial chaos. The throne-vision framework "
                               "(the Head of Days seated) places these cosmological "
                               "secrets within the context of divine governance.",

        "sections": [
            {
                "heading": "The Noahic Voice (60:1-6)",
                "body": "This chapter shifts to Noah as the speaker (or Enoch "
                        "speaking as Noah — the textual tradition is confused). "
                        "The shift is part of a broader pattern of Noahic "
                        "interpolations in 1 Enoch (cf. chapters 65-68). The "
                        "Head of Days on the throne causes trembling — the "
                        "theophanic fear response present throughout the Enochic "
                        "tradition."
            },
            {
                "heading": "Leviathan and Behemoth Separated (60:7-10)",
                "body": "The female sea monster Leviathan and the male land monster "
                        "Behemoth are separated at creation because no single realm "
                        "could contain both. Leviathan occupies 'the abysses of "
                        "the ocean' while Behemoth is in 'the waste wilderness named "
                        "Duidain' (location uncertain). 4 Ezra 6:49-52 preserves "
                        "the same tradition. The two monsters in Revelation 13 "
                        "(beast from the sea, beast from the earth) likely draw on "
                        "this tradition."
            },
            {
                "heading": "Cosmological Secrets (60:11-25)",
                "body": "The chapter concludes with a catalogue of meteorological "
                        "and cosmological secrets: the spirits of thunder, the "
                        "treasury of hail, the spirit of mist, the spirit of dew, "
                        "the secrets of the deep. This is wisdom literature in "
                        "apocalyptic dress — the same knowledge celebrated in Job "
                        "38-41 and Proverbs 8 is here presented as revealed "
                        "through Enochic vision."
            }
        ]
    },

    {
        "id": "1en-61",
        "ref": "1 Enoch 61",
        "chapter_num": 61,
        "title": "The Measuring of the Righteous — Preparation for Judgment",
        "era": "parables",
        "type": "chapter",

        "synopsis": "Angels go forth to 'measure' — surveying the faithful and "
                    "their deeds before the great judgment. The righteous and "
                    "elect shall be preserved, and all the angels 'shall bless "
                    "and glorify and extol' the name of the Lord of Spirits. "
                    "This chapter is the prelude to the great enthronement scene "
