    {
        "id": "1en-62",
        "ref": "1 Enoch 62",
        "chapter_num": 62,
        "title": "The Son of Man on the Throne of Glory — The Great Assize",
        "era": "parables",
        "type": "chapter",

        "synopsis": "The climactic enthronement: the Son of Man sits on the 'throne "
                    "of his glory' and the spirit of righteousness is poured out "
                    "upon him. The kings and mighty see him enthroned and are seized "
                    "with pain. They fall on their faces and beg for mercy, but it "
                    "is too late. The righteous are clothed in 'garments of glory' "
                    "and shall eat, lie down, and rise with the Son of Man forever. "
                    "This is the Parables' most fully realized judgment scene and "
                    "the closest pre-Christian parallel to Matthew 25:31-46.",

        "key_verse": {
            "ref": "1 Enoch 62:5",
            "text": "And pain shall seize them when they see that Son of Man "
                    "sitting on the throne of his glory.",
            "translation": "Charles"
        },

        "hebrew_terms": [],

        "ane_backdrop": "Royal judgment scenes — a divine or divinely appointed figure "
                        "on a throne rendering verdicts — are among the oldest ANE "
                        "literary motifs. Egyptian Osiris presides over the Hall of "
                        "Maat. The Parables' innovation is placing a second figure "
                        "(not the Most High) on the judgment throne.",

        "second_temple": [
            {
                "source": "Psalms of Solomon 17:21-46",
                "summary": "The Lord's anointed purges Jerusalem, judges nations, and "
                           "establishes a righteous kingdom.",
                "relevance": "A contemporary messianic expectation focused on a Davidic "
                             "warrior-king. The Parables combine this with the Danielic "
                             "Son of Man.",
                "canon": False
            }
        ],

        "cross_refs": [
            {"ref": "Matthew 25:31-46", "note": "'When the Son of Man comes in his glory and sits on his glorious throne' — the most direct NT parallel, shared vocabulary (throne of glory, separation, punishment)", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Daniel 7:13-14", "note": "One like a son of man given dominion — the source the Parables develop into a full enthronement narrative", "type": "ot"},
            {"ref": "Psalm 110:1-2", "note": "'Sit at my right hand until I make your enemies your footstool' — the enthronement psalm", "type": "ot"},
            {"ref": "Philippians 2:10-11", "note": "'Every knee should bow' — the universal acknowledgment that 1 Enoch 62 describes when kings prostrate themselves", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Revelation 19:11-16", "note": "The rider who judges and makes war in righteousness — the Apocalypse's enthroned Judge", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Acts 7:55-56", "note": "Stephen sees the Son of Man standing at the right hand of God — the enthroned figure visible to a dying witness", "type": "nt"}
        ],

        "divine_council_note": "1 Enoch 62 represents the fullest realization of "
                               "delegated judgment in the divine council. The Lord of "
                               "Spirits places the Elect One on the throne, and the "
                               "Elect One exercises the judicial function that in the "
                               "OT belongs to YHWH alone (Psalm 96:13). The same logic "
                               "underlies John 5:22 ('The Father has given all judgment "
                               "to the Son') and Acts 17:31.",

        "sections": [
            {
                "heading": "The Enthronement (62:1-4)",
                "body": "The Lord of Spirits commands the Elect One to sit on the "
                        "throne of glory. 'The spirit of righteousness was poured "
                        "out upon him, and the word of his mouth slays all sinners' "
                        "(62:2) — echoing Isaiah 11:4 and anticipating Revelation "
                        "19:15. The judgment word is a performative utterance that "
                        "accomplishes what it declares."
            },
            {
                "heading": "The Agony of the Kings (62:5-12)",
                "body": "When kings see the Son of Man enthroned, 'pain shall seize "
                        "them' (62:5). They prostrate themselves and 'beg and "
                        "petition for mercy' (62:9). But mercy is unavailable: "
                        "recognition comes too late. This directly anticipates "
                        "Jesus' warning in Matthew 7:22-23: 'Lord, Lord!' — 'I "
                        "never knew you.' The kings' confession: 'We have not "
                        "believed before Him nor glorified the name of the Lord "
                        "of Spirits, but our hope was in the sceptre of our "
                        "kingdom, and in our glory' (63:7)."
            },
            {
                "heading": "The Joy of the Righteous (62:13-16)",
                "body": "The righteous 'shall never thenceforward see the face of "
                        "the sinners' (62:13). They eat, lie down, and rise with "
                        "the Son of Man forever. They are clothed in 'garments of "
                        "glory' — the 'white robes' of Revelation 6:11 and 7:9. "
                        "The contrast is total: the mighty who trusted in power "
                        "are destroyed; the righteous are glorified. This great "
                        "reversal is the Parables' central ethical message."
            }
        ]
    },

    {
        "id": "1en-63",
        "ref": "1 Enoch 63",
        "chapter_num": 63,
        "title": "The Confession of the Kings — Too Late for Mercy",
        "era": "parables",
        "type": "chapter",

        "synopsis": "The kings and mighty ones make their confession before the Son "
                    "of Man. They acknowledge their sins: they glorified themselves, "
                    "denied the Lord of Spirits, and trusted in their own scepter "
                    "and glory. They beg for a brief respite to offer worship. "
                    "But they are delivered to the angels of punishment. The "
                    "confession comes too late.",

        "key_verse": {
            "ref": "1 Enoch 63:7",
            "text": "We have not believed before Him nor glorified the name of "
                    "the Lord of Spirits, nor glorified our Lord, but our hope "
                    "was in the sceptre of our kingdom, and in our glory.",
            "translation": "Charles"
        },

        "hebrew_terms": [],
        "ane_backdrop": None,
        "second_temple": [],

        "cross_refs": [
            {"ref": "Philippians 2:10-11", "note": "Every knee bows and every tongue confesses — but in the Parables, as in Philippians, the confession of hostile powers is forced, not voluntary", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "James 2:19", "note": "'Even the demons believe — and shudder' — belief under compulsion is not saving faith", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Revelation 6:15-17", "note": "Kings and the mighty hide in caves and cry to the mountains to fall on them — the same futile response as the Parables' kings", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Luke 13:25-28", "note": "'Lord, open to us' — 'I do not know where you come from. Depart from me' — the same pattern of belated recognition and denied entry", "type": "nt"}
        ],

        "divine_council_note": "The kings' confession is a courtroom admission of "
                               "guilt, not a genuine repentance. The council accepts "
                               "the confession as evidence but grants no clemency. "
                               "The 'angels of punishment' execute the sentence.",

        "sections": [
            {
                "heading": "The Confession (63:1-7)",
                "body": "The kings and mighty confess three specific sins: (1) they "
                        "'glorified ourselves' — self-exaltation in place of "
                        "worshipping God; (2) they 'denied the Lord of Spirits' "
                        "— the defining sin of the Parables; (3) they placed their "
                        "'hope in the sceptre of our kingdom' — reliance on human "
                        "power. This three-part confession perfectly inverts what "
                        "the righteous do: the righteous glorify God, acknowledge "
                        "the Lord of Spirits, and place hope in him."
            },
            {
                "heading": "No Mercy — The Irrevocable Verdict (63:8-12)",
                "body": "The kings beg for 'a little breathing-space' but are "
                        "denied. The verdict is irrevocable. This theological "
                        "position — that there comes a point beyond which "
                        "repentance is no longer accepted — appears in Hebrews "
                        "6:4-6 ('impossible to restore again to repentance') and "
                        "the blasphemy against the Holy Spirit (Mark 3:29). The "
                        "Parables present the eschatological judgment as final: "
                        "once the Son of Man is enthroned and the verdict rendered, "
                        "there is no appeal."
            }
        ]
    },

