    {
        "id": "1en-69",
        "ref": "1 Enoch 69",
        "chapter_num": 69,
        "title": "The Name and the Oath — The Creative Power of the Divine Word",
        "era": "parables",
        "type": "chapter",

        "synopsis": "Chapter 69 contains a remarkable passage about the creative "
                    "power of the divine name. By a great oath (shevuah), the "
                    "heavens were suspended, the earth founded, the luminaries "
                    "set in their courses, and the sea contained. This oath-name "
                    "is the creative word by which reality was spoken into being. "
                    "The Son of Man then sits on the throne of glory, and judgment "
                    "is given to him. Sinners pass away; those who led the world "
                    "astray are imprisoned.",

        "key_verse": {
            "ref": "1 Enoch 69:27-29",
            "text": "And he sat on the throne of his glory, and the sum of "
                    "judgement was given unto the Son of Man, and he caused the "
                    "sinners to pass away and be destroyed from off the face of "
                    "the earth, and those who have led the world astray. With "
                    "chains shall they be bound, and in their assemblage-place "
                    "of destruction shall they be imprisoned.",
            "translation": "Charles"
        },

        "hebrew_terms": [],

        "ane_backdrop": "The creative power of the divine name/word resonates with "
                        "Egyptian theology (Ptah creates through speech — the "
                        "Memphite Theology) and with Mesopotamian traditions where "
                        "divine utterance establishes cosmic order. The Hebrew "
                        "tradition of creation by speech (Genesis 1: 'Let there "
                        "be...') is the immediate background. The 'oath' by which "
                        "creation is sustained is a unique Enochic concept that "
                        "the cosmos is maintained by a covenantal word.",

        "second_temple": [],

        "cross_refs": [
            {"ref": "John 1:1-3", "note": "'In the beginning was the Word... all things were made through him' — the Logos as creative agent parallels the Parables' oath-name", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Hebrews 1:3", "note": "Christ 'upholds the universe by the word of his power' — the sustaining divine word that parallels the oath holding creation together", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Colossians 1:17", "note": "'In him all things hold together' — the cosmic-sustaining function of the divine word/name", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Genesis 1:3-26", "note": "Creation by divine speech: 'Let there be...' — the background for the oath-name's creative power", "type": "ot"},
            {"ref": "Psalm 33:6, 9", "note": "'By the word of the LORD the heavens were made... he spoke, and it came to be' — the creative word tradition", "type": "ot"}
        ],

        "divine_council_note": "The oath-name by which creation was established and is "
                               "sustained is the ultimate council secret. The Son of "
                               "Man's enthronement and judgment authority derive from "
                               "the same creative word: the one who sustains the cosmos "
                               "has the authority to judge it.",

        "sections": [
            {
                "heading": "The Oath of Creation (69:13-25)",
                "body": "By a 'great oath,' the heavens were 'suspended before the "
                        "world was created,' the earth founded on water, the "
                        "luminaries set in their courses, and the sea contained "
                        "(69:16-25). This oath-name is the creative word itself — "
                        "the power by which reality coheres. The concept parallels "
                        "John 1:1-3 (the Logos through whom all things were made) "
                        "and Hebrews 1:3 (the Son who 'upholds the universe by the "
                        "word of his power'). The Parables present a cosmos held "
                        "together by a divine covenantal word — a theological "
                        "concept that influenced both Jewish mysticism (the "
                        "creative power of divine names) and Christian Logos "
                        "theology."
            },
            {
                "heading": "The Son of Man Enthroned (69:26-29)",
                "body": "The chapter's climax: the Son of Man sits on the throne of "
                        "glory, and 'the sum of judgement was given unto' him "
                        "(69:27). He causes sinners to 'pass away and be destroyed "
                        "from off the face of the earth' and imprisons those who "
                        "'led the world astray' (69:28). The connection between "
                        "creation and judgment is deliberate: the same authority "
                        "that established the world will dissolve the wicked. This "
                        "is the theological link between the oath-name and the "
                        "enthronement — both are expressions of the same divine power."
            }
        ]
    },

