    {
        "id": "1en-71",
        "ref": "1 Enoch 71",
        "chapter_num": 71,
        "title": "You Are the Son of Man — Enoch's Identification and Exaltation",
        "era": "parables",
        "type": "chapter",

        "synopsis": "The climactic conclusion of the Book of Parables. Enoch's "
                    "spirit is translated into the heaven of heavens. He falls on "
                    "his face before the Head of Days, whose head is 'white and "
                    "pure as wool.' His whole body melts and his spirit is "
                    "transfigured. The Head of Days comes to him and greets him "
                    "with the words: 'Thou art the Son of Man who is born unto "
                    "righteousness, and righteousness abides over thee.' This "
                    "identification of Enoch as the Son of Man is the most "
                    "debated verse in all of Second Temple literature.",

        "key_verse": {
            "ref": "1 Enoch 71:14",
            "text": "And he came to me and greeted me with His voice, and said "
                    "unto me: 'Thou art the Son of Man who is born unto "
                    "righteousness, and righteousness abides over thee, and the "
                    "righteousness of the Head of Days forsakes thee not.'",
            "translation": "Charles"
        },

        "hebrew_terms": [],

        "ane_backdrop": "The concept of a human elevated to divine status has deep "
                        "ANE precedent. Utnapishtim receives immortality after the "
                        "flood. Adapa is brought before the gods. Enmeduranki is "
                        "taken into the divine assembly. Egyptian pharaohs become "
                        "Osiris after death. The Greek apotheosis tradition describes "
                        "humans becoming divine. 1 Enoch 71 is the Jewish version "
                        "filtered through divine council theology.",

        "second_temple": [
            {
                "source": "3 Enoch (Sefer Hekhalot)",
                "summary": "Enoch is transformed into Metatron, 'the lesser YHWH,' "
                           "given a throne and authority over all the angels.",
                "relevance": "The full development of 1 Enoch 71's tradition: from "
                             "Son of Man to Lesser YHWH. The trajectory from Gen 5:24 "
                             "to 1 En 71 to 3 Enoch shows increasing divinization.",
                "canon": False
            },
            {
                "source": "2 Enoch 22:8-10 (Slavonic Enoch)",
                "summary": "God instructs Michael to anoint Enoch and clothe him in "
                           "'garments of My glory.' Enoch becomes 'like one of His "
                           "glorious ones, and there was no difference.'",
                "relevance": "Independent witness to Enoch's glorification tradition.",
                "canon": False
            }
        ],

        "cross_refs": [
            {"ref": "Genesis 5:24", "note": "'Enoch walked with God, and he was not, for God took him' — the seed text from which 1 Enoch 71 ultimately grows", "type": "ot"},
            {"ref": "Daniel 7:13-14", "note": "'One like a son of man' given dominion — the figure whom chapter 71 identifies as Enoch", "type": "ot"},
            {"ref": "Matthew 17:2", "note": "Jesus' transfiguration — 'his face shone like the sun' — parallels Enoch's 'my spirit was transfigured' (71:11)", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Philippians 2:9-11", "note": "'God highly exalted him and gave him the name above every name' — the NT's version of human exaltation to divine status", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Philippians 3:20-21", "note": "Christ 'will transform our lowly body to be like his glorious body' — the pattern of transformation 1 Enoch 71 anticipates", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Revelation 3:21", "note": "'I will grant him to sit with me on my throne' — a human sharing the divine throne, as Enoch/Son of Man does", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Hebrews 1:3", "note": "'He sat down at the right hand of the Majesty on high' — the exalted human on the divine throne", "type": "nt"},
            {"ref": "Acts 2:33", "note": "'Being therefore exalted at the right hand of God' — the human Jesus raised to the divine council position", "type": "nt"}
        ],

        "divine_council_note": "1 Enoch 71 is the most radical divine council text in "
                               "all of Second Temple literature. A human being is not "
                               "merely admitted to the council but identified AS the "
                               "enthroned second figure. The Son of Man who sits on the "
                               "throne of glory and judges all creation IS the translated "
                               "patriarch of Genesis 5:24. The theological implications "
                               "are staggering: the boundary between divine and human, "
                               "which the Watchers transgressed downward, can also be "
                               "crossed upward — by divine invitation. This provides the "
                               "template for the NT's claim that Jesus, fully human, sits "
                               "at the right hand of God (Acts 2:33, Heb 1:3).",

        "sections": [
            {
                "heading": "The Throne Vision (71:1-10)",
                "body": "Enoch's spirit is 'translated into the heaven of heavens' "
                        "(71:1). He sees walls of crystal, tongues of fire, and the "
                        "seraphim, cherubim, and ophanim — the full complement of "
                        "throne-room beings from Isaiah 6, Ezekiel 1, and the "
                        "Enochic tradition. He falls on his face before the Head of "
                        "Days. 'My whole body melted, and my spirit was transfigured' "
                        "(71:11) — the language of transformation in the divine "
                        "presence parallels Moses' shining face (Exodus 34:29-35), "
                        "Jesus' transfiguration (Matthew 17:2), and Paul's 'we are "
                        "being transformed into the same image from one degree of "
                        "glory to another' (2 Corinthians 3:18)."
            },
            {
                "heading": "The Identification — 'Thou Art the Son of Man' (71:14-17)",
                "body": "The Head of Days himself addresses Enoch: 'Thou art the Son "
                        "of Man who is born unto righteousness' (71:14). This is one "
                        "of the most debated verses in all of Second Temple literature. "
                        "On the surface, it identifies Enoch — a human patriarch — as "
                        "the pre-existent, enthroned Son of Man who has been the "
                        "subject of the entire Book of Parables. Some scholars "
                        "(Charles, Black) argue chapter 71 is a later addition that "
                        "contradicts the earlier chapters where the Son of Man appears "
                        "to be a distinct pre-existent being. Others (VanderKam, "
                        "Nickelsburg) accept it as original and invoke the concept of "
                        "a 'heavenly double' — a pre-existent celestial identity that "
                        "Enoch 'becomes' at his translation. This concept appears in "
                        "other Jewish texts (the angel Israel in the Prayer of Joseph, "
                        "Abel as heavenly judge in the Testament of Abraham). If "
                        "correct, Enoch's translation (Gen 5:24) is his reunion with "
                        "his pre-existent heavenly self."
            },
            {
                "heading": "Implications for Christology (71:14-17)",
                "body": "Whatever the original authorial intent, the theological "
                        "implication of 71:14 is clear: a human being can be exalted "
                        "to the highest position in the divine hierarchy, sharing the "
                        "throne with the Head of Days. This is the template for the "
                        "early Christian claim that Jesus of Nazareth was exalted to "
                        "God's right hand and given 'the name above every name' "
                        "(Philippians 2:9-11). The Parables show that such a claim "
                        "was intelligible — indeed, already being made — within "
                        "pre-Christian Judaism. The pattern of thought (a human who "
                        "'is' a pre-existent heavenly being) was available in Jewish "
                        "theology before Christianity articulated it about Jesus. "
                        "The later development in 3 Enoch, where Enoch becomes "
                        "Metatron, the 'Lesser YHWH' seated on a throne in heaven, "
                        "shows this trajectory carried forward. The rabbis would "
                        "eventually reject this 'two thrones' theology as heretical "
                        "(b. Hagigah 15a: 'Perhaps there are two powers in heaven?'), "
                        "but the Parables demonstrate it was once a live option "
                        "within mainstream Jewish angelology."
            }
        ]
    },

